  "doc_id": "37946",
  "text": "Mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs) are evolutionarily conserved signal transduction enzymes that are activated in response to diverse extracellular inputs ranging from stress signals, to mitogens, to developmental cues [CITATION_1] . MAPKs are activated by dual-specificity MAPK kinases (MAP2Ks) that phosphorylate a conserved threonine (T) and tyrosine (Y) in the activation loop of the MAPK. MAP2Ks are activated by upstream kinases (MAP3Ks) that couple to receptors through a variety of mechanisms (canonical MAPK signaling). MAPKs are also activated by noncanonical mechanisms [CITATION_2] . These alternative mechanisms include phosphorylation of MAPKs by kinases outside of the MAP2K family and autophosphorylation.",
